<doc id="1211913" wikidata="Q6134913" url="?curid=1211913" title="Least fixed point">
<text>In order theory, a branch of mathematics, the least fixed point (lfp or LFP, sometimes also smallest fixed point) of a function from a partially ordered set (&quot;poset&quot; for short) to itself is the fixed point which is less than each other fixed point, according to the order of the poset. A function need not have a least fixed point, but if it does then the least fixed point is unique.

==Examples==
With the usual order on the real numbers, the least fixed point of the real function &quot;f&quot;(&quot;x&quot;) = &quot;x&quot;2 is &quot;x&quot; = 0 (since the only other fixed point is 1 and 0 &lt; 1). In contrast, &quot;f&quot;(&quot;x&quot;) = &quot;x&quot; + 1 has no fixed points at all, so has no least one, and &quot;f&quot;(&quot;x&quot;) = &quot;x&quot; has infinitely many fixed points, but has no least one.

Let formula_1 be a directed graph and formula_2 be a vertex. The set of vertices accessible from formula_2 can be defined as the least fixed-point of the function formula_4, defined as formula_5
The set of vertices which are co-accessible from formula_2 is defined by a similar least fix-point. The strongly connected component of formula_2 is the intersection of those two least fixed-points.

Let formula_8 be a context-free grammar. The set formula_9 of symbols which produces the empty string formula_10 can be obtained as the least fixed-point of the function formula_4, defined as formula_12, where formula_13 denotes the power set of formula_14.

==Applications==
Many fixed-point theorems yield algorithms for locating the least fixed point. Least fixed points often have desirable properties that arbitrary fixed points do not.

===Denotational semantics===
In computer science, the &quot;denotational semantics&quot; approach uses least fixed points to obtain from a given program text a corresponding mathematical function, called its semantics. To this end, an artificial mathematical object, formula_15, is introduced, denoting the exceptional value &quot;undefined&quot;.
Given e.g. the program datatype codice_1, its mathematical counterpart is defined as formula_16
it is made a partially ordered set by defining formula_17 for each formula_18 and letting any two different members formula_19 be uncomparable w.r.t. formula_20, see picture. 

The semantics of a program definition codice_2 is some mathematical function formula_21 If the program definition codice_3 does not terminate for some input codice_4, this can be expressed mathematically as formula_22 The set of all mathematical functions is made partially ordered by defining formula_23 if, for each formula_24 the relation formula_25 holds, that is, if formula_26 is less defined or equal to formula_27 For example, the semantics of the expression codice_5 is less defined than that of codice_6, since the former, but not the latter, maps formula_28 to formula_29 and they agree otherwise.

Given some program text codice_3, its mathematical counterpart is obtained as least fixed point of some mapping from functions to functions that can be obtained by &quot;translating&quot; codice_3.
For example, the C definition 
int fact(int n) { if (n == 0) return 1; else return n * fact(n-1); }
is translated to a mapping 
:formula_30 defined as formula_31 
The mapping formula_32 is defined in a non-recursive way, although codice_9 was defined recursively.
Under certain restrictions (see Kleene fixed-point theorem), which are met in the example, formula_32 necessarily has a least fixed point, formula_34, that is formula_35 for all formula_36. 
It is possible to show that 
:formula_37 

A larger fixed point of formula_32 is e.g. the function formula_39 defined by 
:formula_40 
however, this function does not correctly reflect the behavior of the above program text for negative formula_41 e.g. the call codice_10 will not terminate at all, let alone return codice_11.
Only the &quot;least&quot; fixed point, formula_42 can reasonably be used as a mathematical program semantic.

===Descriptive complexity===
Immerman
and Vardi
independently showed the descriptive complexity result that the polynomial-time computable properties of linearly ordered structures are definable in FO(LFP), i.e. in first-order logic with a least fixed point operator. However, FO(LFP) is too weak to express all polynomial-time properties of unordered structures (for instance that a structure has even size).

==Greatest fixed points==
The greatest fixed point of a function can be defined analogously to the least fixed point, as the fixed point which is greater than any other fixed point, according to the order of the poset. In computer science, greatest fixed points are much less commonly used than least fixed points. Specifically, the posets found in domain theory usually do not have a greatest element, hence for a given function, there may be multiple, mutually incomparable maximal fixed points, and the greatest fixed point of that function may not exist. To address this issue, the &quot;optimal fixed point&quot; has been defined as the most-defined fixed point compatible with all other fixed points. The optimal fixed point always exists, and is the greatest fixed point if the greatest fixed point exists. The optimal fixed point allows formal study of recursive and corecursive functions that do not converge with the least fixed point. Unfortunately, whereas Kleene&#x27;s recursion theorem shows that the least fixed point is effectively computable, the optimal fixed point of a computable function may be a non-computable function.

